equals() and hashCode() in Java

equals() and hashCode() are methods from the Object class.

They are used to compare objects and are especially important when working with collections like HashMap and HashSet.

equals() method

equals() is used to compare object content, not references.

Default behavior
Object a = new Object();
Object b = new Object();

a.equals(b); // false

👉 By default, it compares memory addresses (same as ==)

Custom equals()
class Person {
    String name;

    public boolean equals(Object o) {
        if (this == o) return true;
        if (o == null || getClass() != o.getClass()) return false;

        Person p = (Person) o;
        return name.equals(p.name);
    }
}

👉 Now objects are compared by name

hashCode() method

hashCode() returns an integer representing the object.

int hash = obj.hashCode();

👉 Used internally in hash-based collections like HashMap

Why hashCode is important

In HashMap:

hashCode() → finds bucket
equals() → compares objects inside bucket

👉 Both methods work together

The Rule (VERY IMPORTANT)

If two objects are equal → they MUST have same hashCode

a.equals(b) == true  →  a.hashCode() == b.hashCode()

❗ If you override equals(), you MUST override hashCode()

Example with both methods
import java.util.Objects;

class Person {
    String name;

    @Override
    public boolean equals(Object o) {
        if (this == o) return true;
        if (!(o instanceof Person)) return false;
        Person p = (Person) o;
        return Objects.equals(name, p.name);
    }

    @Override
    public int hashCode() {
        return Objects.hash(name);
    }
}
What happens if you don’t override hashCode?

👉 Bugs in HashMap / HashSet

Example:

two objects look equal
but stored in different buckets
result → duplicates or failed search
equals vs ==
equals()	==
compares content	compares references
can be overridden	cannot be changed
Summary
equals() → compares object content
hashCode() → used for hashing (fast lookup)
always override both together
critical for HashMap, HashSet

